1
00:01:27,654 --> 00:01:29,144
In Vienna in 1844

2
00:01:29,222 --> 00:01:31,747
nice people neither danced the waltz

3
00:01:31,825 --> 00:01:33,850
nor kissed their wives

4
00:01:33,960 --> 00:01:36,554
in public nor listened to new ideas

5
00:01:36,629 --> 00:01:38,961
In 1845 came Johann Strauss II and

6
00:01:39,032 --> 00:01:40,829
his immortal melodies

7
00:01:40,900 --> 00:01:42,834
We've dramatized his spirit

8
00:01:42,902 --> 00:01:44,699
rather than facts of his life

9
00:01:44,804 --> 00:01:46,533
because it's his spirit that has lived
in his music

10
00:01:48,808 --> 00:01:55,111
VIENNA KK COMMERCIAL BANK

11
00:02:11,798 --> 00:02:14,824
Just a minute, my dear Mr. Strauss... 

12
00:02:15,568 --> 00:02:17,229
and what's this?

13
00:02:17,637 --> 00:02:18,399
A waltz

14
00:02:18,438 --> 00:02:21,032
Another waltz, I see

15
00:02:21,307 --> 00:02:23,775
Mr. Strauss, your father persuaded me

16
00:02:23,877 --> 00:02:26,004
to take you in against my judgment

17
00:02:26,079 --> 00:02:28,946
And what's my reward?

18
00:02:28,982 --> 00:02:30,745
Every time I turn around,

19
00:02:30,817 --> 00:02:32,808
there's another waltz printed on this paper

20
00:02:32,886 --> 00:02:33,750
This is all... 

21
00:02:33,853 --> 00:02:34,820
Don't... you don't

22
00:02:34,888 --> 00:02:35,912
You know, those are mine

23
00:02:35,989 --> 00:02:38,116
You've got me a 60,000 golden

24
00:02:38,158 --> 00:02:39,750
And you've got my waltz

25
00:02:42,595 --> 00:02:46,895
And now, get over then... you're fired

26
00:02:47,066 --> 00:02:49,330
Join those revolutionaries... 

27
00:02:50,069 --> 00:02:52,162
they won't go to work either

28
00:02:53,506 --> 00:02:56,998
No fuss, no frank than serve in the street

29
00:02:57,076 --> 00:02:59,044
to start another revolution

30
00:03:00,980 --> 00:03:02,004
Now, Mr. Wertheimer... 

31
00:03:02,115 --> 00:03:03,412
Get out

32
00:03:05,318 --> 00:03:08,014
Thanks for firing me, Mr. Wertheimer

33
00:03:08,154 --> 00:03:09,985
Goodbye, you worms

34
00:03:16,629 --> 00:03:19,462
KK COMMERCIAL BANK

35
00:03:43,089 --> 00:03:46,217
Bless you, son... 
Mr. Wertheimer closed today?

36
00:03:46,893 --> 00:03:49,259
Well, perhaps they run out of money

37
00:03:49,362 --> 00:03:50,761
One half of the bank is still open

38
00:03:50,830 --> 00:03:53,298
The bank is still open... 
but we're not in it

39
00:03:53,700 --> 00:03:55,827
A nice happy holiday, Johann?

40
00:03:55,902 --> 00:03:56,300
Yes

41
00:03:56,369 --> 00:03:57,529
Yes

42
00:03:57,637 --> 00:04:00,629
Is... is Poldi around?

43
00:04:00,707 --> 00:04:03,403
Ah, he wants to see Poldi... 
Mama, you hear?

44
00:04:03,443 --> 00:04:07,004
Sure... I thought he maybe came to see you

45
00:04:07,547 --> 00:04:10,880
If you please, Mr. Finance Minister

46
00:04:12,919 --> 00:04:15,387
Look what the mailman brought you?

47
00:04:15,455 --> 00:04:18,913
Johann... hello, Johann

48
00:04:18,958 --> 00:04:21,153
Hello, Poldi, what... what are you doing?

49
00:04:21,728 --> 00:04:23,457
What am I doing?

50
00:04:23,529 --> 00:04:25,190
What are you doing here?

51
00:04:25,231 --> 00:04:27,699
This is wonderful in the middle
of the day

52
00:04:27,767 --> 00:04:29,496
How did you get away from the bank?

53
00:04:29,569 --> 00:04:31,935
Well, l... I just walk out

54
00:04:33,706 --> 00:04:36,174
Johann, something is the matter?

55
00:04:36,242 --> 00:04:38,142
Is something happening?

56
00:04:38,211 --> 00:04:41,112
Oh, nothing... nothing that
I don't want to happen

57
00:04:43,816 --> 00:04:45,181
What's happening, Johann?

58
00:04:45,251 --> 00:04:46,309
What's happening... ?

59
00:04:46,386 --> 00:04:47,410
I've... I've been fired

60
00:04:47,520 --> 00:04:48,953
That's what's happening

61
00:04:50,690 --> 00:04:52,385
Oh, I'm sorry, Poldi

62
00:04:52,458 --> 00:04:54,323
I didn't mean to yell at you

63
00:04:54,394 --> 00:04:55,884
That's alright

64
00:04:55,962 --> 00:04:58,453
Man has right to yell when
he has been fired

65
00:04:58,531 --> 00:05:01,022
You always seem to know when
I'm in trouble, don't you?

66
00:05:01,100 --> 00:05:03,933
Johann, shall I guess what are you
doing at the bank?

67
00:05:04,704 --> 00:05:07,832
Alright, you guess I'm writing
waltz again

68
00:05:08,508 --> 00:05:10,703
Oh, Johann, don't be rude... 

69
00:05:10,777 --> 00:05:12,608
there're other banks in the world

70
00:05:12,679 --> 00:05:15,876
Maybe Mr. Wertheimer is going
to give you another chance

71
00:05:15,948 --> 00:05:17,347
But I don't want another chance

72
00:05:17,417 --> 00:05:18,349
I'm glad he has fired me

73
00:05:18,418 --> 00:05:19,248
Now I'm free

74
00:05:19,319 --> 00:05:20,308
Who's free?

75
00:05:20,386 --> 00:05:23,651
I am... free to do I've always wanted to... 

76
00:05:23,690 --> 00:05:25,487
free to write music

77
00:05:26,159 --> 00:05:27,751
I quit the bank

78
00:05:28,227 --> 00:05:29,251
You quit the bank?

79
00:05:29,329 --> 00:05:30,296
Hm

80
00:05:30,363 --> 00:05:32,422
But your Papa wanted you to become a banker... 

81
00:05:32,498 --> 00:05:33,965
to have a career

82
00:05:34,167 --> 00:05:36,032
You call banking a career?

83
00:05:36,102 --> 00:05:37,967
Do you know what career is?

84
00:05:38,037 --> 00:05:40,062
Have you heard of Mozart, Schubert and
Beethoven?

85
00:05:40,139 --> 00:05:41,834
They had what I call a career

86
00:05:41,908 --> 00:05:43,239
Did they make money?

87
00:05:43,943 --> 00:05:45,570
They made glorious music

88
00:05:45,645 --> 00:05:46,771
Yes, Papa, that's right... 

89
00:05:46,846 --> 00:05:47,835
they made glorious music

90
00:05:47,880 --> 00:05:49,780
Yeah... I heard their music

91
00:05:50,049 --> 00:05:51,516
Johann, if you want to write waltz... 

92
00:05:51,584 --> 00:05:52,642
you write waltzes

93
00:05:52,752 --> 00:05:53,776
And I play them... 

94
00:05:53,853 --> 00:05:57,050
I play them the way
I always felt they should be played

95
00:05:57,123 --> 00:05:58,784
I'll organize my own orchestra

96
00:05:59,125 --> 00:06:00,285
But how?

97
00:06:00,660 --> 00:06:02,753
You don't have a penny in your pocket

98
00:06:02,862 --> 00:06:06,093
Oh... musicians don't play for nothing

99
00:06:06,199 --> 00:06:07,860
Oh, they don't, do they?

100
00:06:07,934 --> 00:06:09,526
Poldi darling, you don't know musicians

101
00:06:09,602 --> 00:06:12,002
Well, I know 50 men who are willing to... 

102
00:06:12,071 --> 00:06:13,971
now you just wait

103
00:06:15,108 --> 00:06:16,040
Kienzl

104
00:06:16,109 --> 00:06:16,666
Yes?

105
00:06:16,709 --> 00:06:19,143
Kienzl, what do you love the most
in the world?

106
00:06:19,212 --> 00:06:20,304
Huh?

107
00:06:20,380 --> 00:06:25,079
Well, sometimes a girl... 
most times a goulash

108
00:06:25,151 --> 00:06:26,709
No... you play violin... 

109
00:06:26,753 --> 00:06:27,879
don't you love your violin?

110
00:06:27,954 --> 00:06:30,582
Yes, but a good beef goulash with... 

111
00:06:30,656 --> 00:06:33,090
Alright... would you like to play
in my orchestra?

112
00:06:33,159 --> 00:06:34,421
When you have an orchestra?

113
00:06:34,494 --> 00:06:36,758
If I have an orchestra, would you like
to play in it?

114
00:06:37,029 --> 00:06:39,429
Well, if you had, you mean for nothing?

115
00:06:39,499 --> 00:06:40,557
But of course for nothing

116
00:06:40,633 --> 00:06:41,190
Is it permanent?

117
00:06:41,267 --> 00:06:41,858
Sure

118
00:06:41,934 --> 00:06:43,799
That's a nice one when you're taking... 

119
00:06:43,870 --> 00:06:45,360
you should take it to the park

120
00:06:45,438 --> 00:06:46,370
Yes, that's a good idea

121
00:06:46,439 --> 00:06:47,406
Look, Kienzl... 

122
00:06:47,473 --> 00:06:48,735
do you know Dudelman
who plays violin?

123
00:06:48,808 --> 00:06:49,604
Hm

124
00:06:49,675 --> 00:06:51,108
And Albert and Duffman?

125
00:06:51,210 --> 00:06:52,370
Where we could get them?

126
00:06:52,412 --> 00:06:53,310
We could get them easily... 

127
00:06:53,379 --> 00:06:55,006
they jump at a chance like this

128
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:57,641
Is this the nice way to entertain
your sweetheart?

129
00:06:57,884 --> 00:06:59,351
Sweetheart?

130
00:06:59,419 --> 00:07:02,183
He doesn't know if I'm standing
on my head or feet

131
00:07:02,355 --> 00:07:05,017
He's so mixed up with his troubles

132
00:07:05,124 --> 00:07:07,149
And I don't blame him

133
00:07:07,393 --> 00:07:11,056
Is this the way to look when a young
man comes to see you?

134
00:07:11,864 --> 00:07:13,661
You know, Poldi

135
00:07:13,733 --> 00:07:16,759
Sometimes it's good for a woman to make
a man think about something else

136
00:07:16,903 --> 00:07:18,803
beside the troubles

137
00:07:18,905 --> 00:07:21,567
How do you think I finally got
your Papa?

138
00:07:22,008 --> 00:07:24,602
Keeping his mind on apple strudel

139
00:07:25,812 --> 00:07:28,679
Now remember... be in my house
at 2 o'clock on Sunday

140
00:07:28,714 --> 00:07:29,476
See, listen... 

141
00:07:29,549 --> 00:07:31,039
I got a cousin who works
at the tea shop

142
00:07:31,117 --> 00:07:31,742
What does he play?

143
00:07:31,818 --> 00:07:33,786
A piccolo for nothing... 
I'd recommend him too

144
00:07:33,853 --> 00:07:35,377
Bring him along

145
00:07:35,755 --> 00:07:36,779
There you're, Poldi... 

146
00:07:36,856 --> 00:07:38,551
there's true musician for you

147
00:07:38,591 --> 00:07:40,320
Money doesn't mean a thing to him... 

148
00:07:40,359 --> 00:07:41,849
he never even thought of it

149
00:07:41,894 --> 00:07:43,759
Johann, whatever career you choose... 

150
00:07:43,830 --> 00:07:45,627
profit will be the very highest

151
00:07:45,731 --> 00:07:48,029
Poldi, you do believe in me, don't you?

152
00:07:48,334 --> 00:07:49,426
You know I do

153
00:07:49,702 --> 00:07:51,397
I could kiss you for that

154
00:07:51,704 --> 00:07:53,433
Yes, Johann

155
00:07:53,706 --> 00:07:56,197
Poldi, you know what?

156
00:07:56,342 --> 00:07:57,206
What?

157
00:07:57,276 --> 00:07:59,710
Popofinger... Hans Popofinger

158
00:07:59,779 --> 00:08:00,507
He's out of the job and

159
00:08:00,580 --> 00:08:02,480
he's the best double bassoon player
in old Vienna

160
00:08:02,582 --> 00:08:05,881
Oh, Poldi... what'll I do without you?

161
00:08:05,952 --> 00:08:08,443
I don't know what you're doing with me

162
00:08:17,263 --> 00:08:19,959
Hey, Mr. Strauss... 

163
00:08:21,634 --> 00:08:23,397
I have an aunt who plays harp

164
00:08:23,469 --> 00:08:24,436
Bring her too

165
00:08:24,504 --> 00:08:25,732
But she's 72 years old

166
00:08:25,805 --> 00:08:28,569
Just put her on the wheelchair and
bring her along

167
00:08:29,509 --> 00:08:30,771
CASINO DOMMAYER:

168
00:08:30,877 --> 00:08:32,538
DEBUT OF JOHANN STRAUSS

169
00:08:32,678 --> 00:08:35,442
AND HIS ORCHESTRA

170
00:09:51,991 --> 00:09:53,549
Excellent

171
00:09:57,730 --> 00:10:00,130
I hope that dropout bank's job is
still there

172
00:10:00,232 --> 00:10:01,096
Shh... 

173
00:10:01,133 --> 00:10:03,328
You have a wonderful son, Mrs. Strauss

174
00:10:03,402 --> 00:10:05,063
I warned him

175
00:10:09,508 --> 00:10:10,566
I'm sorry

176
00:10:10,676 --> 00:10:11,700
So am I

177
00:10:11,777 --> 00:10:14,678
But don't take it much too hard... 
young Strauss

178
00:10:14,747 --> 00:10:16,408
You know Beethoven was not a success

179
00:10:16,482 --> 00:10:18,507
either the first time he waved his baritone

180
00:10:18,584 --> 00:10:20,711
But gentlemen, I thank you very much

181
00:10:20,786 --> 00:10:23,380
There's some goulash in the kitchen
on your way out

182
00:10:25,958 --> 00:10:29,359
Boys, open the windows and
start your cleaning

183
00:10:29,428 --> 00:10:32,659
Ladies and gentlemen... 
the performance is over

184
00:10:33,432 --> 00:10:37,994
I'm very sorry, but the Dommayer
is to close early tonight

185
00:10:38,070 --> 00:10:39,731
But I just paid for ticket and
call for a concert

186
00:10:39,805 --> 00:10:40,430
Let's have it

187
00:10:40,473 --> 00:10:42,407
We'll be glad to refund the money... 

188
00:10:42,441 --> 00:10:44,500
but you see the performance is over

189
00:10:44,577 --> 00:10:45,475
But we don't want the money

190
00:10:45,544 --> 00:10:48,012
We want the music and the performance
is not over

191
00:10:48,080 --> 00:10:50,378
Just a minute, please... 

192
00:10:50,616 --> 00:10:54,052
I'm Aucust Dommayer, owner of
Dommayer's Casino and

193
00:10:54,120 --> 00:10:56,315
the performance is over

194
00:10:56,355 --> 00:10:57,083
And I'm Fritz Cellist,

195
00:10:57,156 --> 00:10:58,953
the first tenor
of the Imperial Opera and

196
00:10:59,025 --> 00:11:01,050
the performance is not over

197
00:11:01,494 --> 00:11:05,794
I don't care who you're... 
the performance is over

198
00:11:07,166 --> 00:11:09,726
The performance is not over

199
00:11:11,804 --> 00:11:16,070
The performance is not over

200
00:11:17,810 --> 00:11:20,210
Hey, what are you doing there?

201
00:11:20,312 --> 00:11:22,837
Leave the windows open

202
00:11:22,948 --> 00:11:26,475
The whole neighborhood might as well
hear it for nothing

203
00:11:27,853 --> 00:11:29,912
Do you have any special wish, Madam?

204
00:11:30,022 --> 00:11:31,353
Anything

205
00:11:34,160 --> 00:11:37,561
Now let's play... 
let's play <Artist's Life>

206
00:11:37,630 --> 00:11:39,530
Now the goulash will be burnt

207
00:11:39,598 --> 00:11:41,088
But it's Carla Donner

208
00:11:41,133 --> 00:11:42,100
Who's she?

209
00:11:42,168 --> 00:11:43,192
Carla Donner

210
00:11:43,269 --> 00:11:45,294
Carla Donner... the famous opera singer

211
00:13:02,348 --> 00:13:04,373
The coach is ready, Madam

212
00:13:04,650 --> 00:13:07,744
Yes, thank you... what time is it?

213
00:13:07,853 --> 00:13:09,218
About 9 o'clock

214
00:13:09,555 --> 00:13:11,079
We must go

215
00:13:15,027 --> 00:13:17,518
Bring him along to the Hall of the
Palace tonight

216
00:13:17,596 --> 00:13:18,893
He might amuse us

217
00:13:18,964 --> 00:13:20,431
Us?

218
00:13:31,744 --> 00:13:34,338
What a stink she is

219
00:13:54,033 --> 00:13:56,399
Guess most people will see us

220
00:13:57,036 --> 00:13:59,596
No extra charge

221
00:13:59,705 --> 00:14:02,640
For nothing they'll listen

222
00:15:49,581 --> 00:15:51,606
Now the <Polka>, you worms

223
00:15:51,684 --> 00:15:54,016
And play as you never play before
in your life

224
00:15:54,086 --> 00:15:55,485
For Vienna

225
00:16:23,415 --> 00:16:25,508
Each man must have a hobby... 

226
00:16:25,551 --> 00:16:27,746
his own kind of hobby

227
00:16:27,886 --> 00:16:29,717
I want beer and girls

228
00:16:29,788 --> 00:16:33,053
I'm fond of girls and beer

229
00:16:33,559 --> 00:16:35,584
But me, I like to stay up

230
00:16:35,661 --> 00:16:37,652
and keep my spirit way up

231
00:16:37,730 --> 00:16:38,697
In a girl I found... 

232
00:16:38,764 --> 00:16:39,958
And songs that sound... 

233
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:44,265
Sound like anyone you hear

234
00:16:44,837 --> 00:16:46,998
Every night in the beat... 

235
00:16:47,106 --> 00:16:53,204
every beat and every hymn... 

236
00:19:37,943 --> 00:19:38,910
What has happened?

237
00:19:38,944 --> 00:19:40,878
Look, Strauss... 

238
00:20:27,492 --> 00:20:30,086
I'm afraid I'm not very elegant
in these clothes

239
00:20:30,495 --> 00:20:31,894
Don't worry

240
00:20:31,964 --> 00:20:35,229
Thanks to Carla Donner... 
others are welcome to town for dinner

241
00:20:35,300 --> 00:20:36,858
in any clothes

242
00:20:37,636 --> 00:20:39,604
Look at our friend Hofbauer... 

243
00:20:39,671 --> 00:20:41,400
why do you think he's here?

244
00:20:41,473 --> 00:20:42,303
Hofbauer?

245
00:20:42,341 --> 00:20:44,332
Do you think he's born in that
dressed shirt?

246
00:20:44,409 --> 00:20:46,809
But he's the greatest music publisher
in Vienna

247
00:20:47,312 --> 00:20:49,405
He's still Hofbauer

248
00:20:55,053 --> 00:20:55,883
Where's Miss Donner?

249
00:20:55,954 --> 00:20:57,012
I don't see her

250
00:20:57,089 --> 00:20:58,750
She'll see you when she wants to

251
00:20:58,824 --> 00:21:00,587
Fritz, I'm so glad you're here... 

252
00:21:00,659 --> 00:21:02,183
take me to supper at once

253
00:21:02,227 --> 00:21:04,889
May I present the young composer of
great talent... 

254
00:21:04,963 --> 00:21:06,294
my friend Johann Strauss... 

255
00:21:06,365 --> 00:21:07,593
Mr. And Mrs. Hofbauer

256
00:21:07,666 --> 00:21:08,860
Oh, how do you do... ?

257
00:21:08,900 --> 00:21:10,527
What nice eyes

258
00:21:10,602 --> 00:21:12,968
Come along, Fritz... 
we'll know each other better

259
00:21:13,071 --> 00:21:15,062
Young man, come along

260
00:21:17,242 --> 00:21:20,040
Patrician, baritone and now
male's contralto

261
00:21:20,112 --> 00:21:21,477
I'm honored, Mr. Hofbauer

262
00:21:21,513 --> 00:21:22,775
Oh, Hofbauer... you know me?

263
00:21:22,814 --> 00:21:25,840
I'm Hofbauer and you... your name?

264
00:21:25,917 --> 00:21:26,406
Strauss

265
00:21:26,485 --> 00:21:28,009
Struass... 

266
00:21:28,420 --> 00:21:30,411
My wife is a lovely woman... 
a lovely woman

267
00:21:30,489 --> 00:21:31,820
Are you a guest here... yes?

268
00:21:31,857 --> 00:21:34,451
Madam Carla Donner was good enough
to invite me here tonight

269
00:21:34,526 --> 00:21:35,049
Carla Donner?

270
00:21:35,127 --> 00:21:36,321
Oh, you watch your step, young man

271
00:21:36,395 --> 00:21:37,453
As far as Carla Donner is concerned... 

272
00:21:37,529 --> 00:21:38,427
Yes?

273
00:21:38,463 --> 00:21:41,762
Come home with the... well, you know

274
00:21:41,800 --> 00:21:44,667
aware to the wife's suspicion... Who are you... ?

275
00:21:44,736 --> 00:21:45,896
I'm a composer

276
00:21:45,937 --> 00:21:46,835
Composer?

277
00:21:46,905 --> 00:21:48,236
Who published you... Shayahara?

278
00:21:48,307 --> 00:21:49,740
Oh, mark my word, young man

279
00:21:49,808 --> 00:21:51,332
If it's not in the print by Hofbauer... 

280
00:21:51,376 --> 00:21:52,604
it's not even music

281
00:21:52,678 --> 00:21:53,906
Mister... 

282
00:21:53,979 --> 00:21:54,843
Strauss

283
00:21:54,913 --> 00:21:56,244
Strauss... I never heard of your music... 

284
00:21:56,315 --> 00:21:57,077
never heard of it

285
00:21:57,149 --> 00:21:58,776
You'll hear it perhaps tonight... 

286
00:21:58,850 --> 00:22:00,442
from Madam Donner herself

287
00:22:00,519 --> 00:22:01,486
if you have no objection

288
00:22:01,520 --> 00:22:03,784
Oh, I have no objection at all, Mister... 

289
00:22:03,955 --> 00:22:05,479
I don't care what your name is... 
I don't care

290
00:22:05,557 --> 00:22:07,286
Smith... Rudolf Smith

291
00:22:07,359 --> 00:22:09,554
Rudolf, goodnight... 

292
00:22:17,669 --> 00:22:19,534
My dear young man, if you... 

293
00:22:20,839 --> 00:22:24,900
well, it's the young man
from the casino, Mister... 

294
00:22:25,077 --> 00:22:27,307
Strauss... Johann Strauss

295
00:22:27,379 --> 00:22:30,109
Madam, I can't tell how... 
how grateful I'm

296
00:22:30,148 --> 00:22:31,581
You're so kind to invite me tonight

297
00:22:31,683 --> 00:22:34,015
Mr. Strauss... Prince Butarka

298
00:22:34,086 --> 00:22:35,485
How do you do?

299
00:22:36,822 --> 00:22:37,811
Mr. Strauss is

300
00:22:37,923 --> 00:22:40,084
the most exciting player in Vienna

301
00:22:41,293 --> 00:22:44,729
After I finish my little wine... 
will you please?

302
00:22:48,834 --> 00:22:51,302
I'm sorry, Madam... 
I didn't mean to interrupt

303
00:22:51,336 --> 00:22:52,997
You did me a favor

304
00:22:53,038 --> 00:22:55,006
Now you can do me another favor

305
00:22:55,073 --> 00:22:56,563
Anything, Madam

306
00:22:56,641 --> 00:22:58,040
Will you please get out of my dress?

307
00:22:58,110 --> 00:22:59,099
Get out?

308
00:22:59,144 --> 00:23:00,702
Oh, I'm so sorry

309
00:23:00,779 --> 00:23:06,115
I have no idea... I seem to be caught

310
00:23:06,551 --> 00:23:07,745
So soon?

311
00:23:08,086 --> 00:23:09,246
What... Madam?

312
00:23:09,654 --> 00:23:12,214
I can simplify everything

313
00:23:14,192 --> 00:23:16,217
But Madam, your gown, l... 

314
00:23:16,328 --> 00:23:17,852
Now tell me... did he ask you to bring

315
00:23:17,929 --> 00:23:19,055
along some of your music?

316
00:23:19,131 --> 00:23:23,295
Yes, Madam, I have a piece here... 
pardon me

317
00:23:23,668 --> 00:23:25,499
Oh, how nice

318
00:23:30,509 --> 00:23:32,807
'Knowing you that you want me'

319
00:23:32,911 --> 00:23:35,209
Did you write the lyrics yourself... 
Mr. Strauss?

320
00:23:35,680 --> 00:23:36,874
Yes, Madam

321
00:23:36,948 --> 00:23:41,214
A lovely idea... you know we're going
to explode a little bomb on ice

322
00:23:41,286 --> 00:23:42,878
I'll sing it

323
00:23:43,021 --> 00:23:45,512
But Madam that... this is a waltz

324
00:23:45,657 --> 00:23:46,749
I know it

325
00:23:46,792 --> 00:23:48,350
You think it's wise?

326
00:23:48,427 --> 00:23:51,362
All these people, I mean your friends... 

327
00:23:51,396 --> 00:23:54,559
maybe they won't think it proper

328
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:56,661
It's time to change their minds

329
00:23:56,735 --> 00:23:58,259
Oh, I see you've already met

330
00:23:58,336 --> 00:24:00,395
Yes, Mr. Strauss,

331
00:24:00,472 --> 00:24:01,996
will you give this
to the leader of the band there?

332
00:24:02,040 --> 00:24:03,166
Yes, Madam

333
00:24:03,208 --> 00:24:05,199
Are you going to sing a waltz here?

334
00:24:05,277 --> 00:24:08,269
I'm going to sing it, but first
you've to announce

335
00:24:08,380 --> 00:24:09,176
Now... Carla?

336
00:24:09,214 --> 00:24:11,079
Now, Fritz

337
00:24:14,853 --> 00:24:16,218
A waltz... 

338
00:24:16,288 --> 00:24:17,084
Ho... 

339
00:24:17,155 --> 00:24:18,281
Where's Madam Donner?

340
00:24:18,356 --> 00:24:19,755
Oh, she's down there with the musicians

341
00:24:19,825 --> 00:24:22,123
What's the idea coming to us... 
even invited musicians?

342
00:24:22,394 --> 00:24:25,295
Huh, they even invited music publishers

343
00:24:27,866 --> 00:24:32,360
Ladies and gentlemen... I've been asked
to direct your attention here

344
00:24:32,437 --> 00:24:36,703
Madam Carla Donner has graciously
consented to sing for us

345
00:24:43,248 --> 00:24:45,011
We won't let them know it's waltz

346
00:24:45,116 --> 00:24:46,947
When we go on to a quarter time,

347
00:24:46,985 --> 00:24:49,977
we let some stalemate and
lift some eye brows

348
00:24:50,021 --> 00:24:52,148
If they lift too far... 
you've to protect me

349
00:24:52,224 --> 00:24:54,055
I can protect you from everything, but... 

350
00:24:54,125 --> 00:24:55,752
But what... Madam?

351
00:24:55,927 --> 00:24:57,622
Tonight I bring you a new song

352
00:24:57,696 --> 00:25:01,188
from a new composer, Mr. Johann Strauss

353
00:25:03,602 --> 00:25:05,797
and I hope his music will attract you

354
00:25:05,871 --> 00:25:06,860
as it does me

355
00:25:06,938 --> 00:25:08,462
He's impostor... an impostor

356
00:25:08,540 --> 00:25:10,565
He tells me his name is Rudolf

357
00:29:16,721 --> 00:29:18,279
Bravo... 

358
00:29:24,195 --> 00:29:26,493
Bravo, Madam

359
00:29:27,398 --> 00:29:29,366
Madam, I can't hardly speak

360
00:29:29,400 --> 00:29:31,732
I don't think the song
will be sung again

361
00:29:31,803 --> 00:29:33,930
It'll never be done so beautifully

362
00:29:35,106 --> 00:29:37,074
Well, the piano alright?

363
00:29:37,175 --> 00:29:39,166
I'm afraid it's tone a little bit hash

364
00:29:39,277 --> 00:29:41,108
I've never heard of it, Madam... 
believe me

365
00:29:41,446 --> 00:29:44,040
Then there's a new one here from Munich

366
00:29:44,115 --> 00:29:45,605
Would you like to try it for me?

367
00:29:45,683 --> 00:29:47,082
Of course, Madam

368
00:29:55,193 --> 00:29:56,888
What a relief... 

369
00:29:57,128 --> 00:29:59,221
I like quiet room, don't you?

370
00:29:59,297 --> 00:30:00,594
Yes, Madam

371
00:30:00,932 --> 00:30:03,093
Now let me see where's the... 

372
00:30:03,168 --> 00:30:04,760
There's no piano... 

373
00:30:04,836 --> 00:30:06,599
quiet rooms don't have pianos

374
00:30:07,438 --> 00:30:09,429
But they have wine

375
00:30:10,241 --> 00:30:14,371
Someone who was very thoughtful... 
wine makes up music

376
00:30:15,079 --> 00:30:16,376
Thank you, Madam

377
00:30:16,447 --> 00:30:18,745
Are you disappointed there's no piano?

378
00:30:19,617 --> 00:30:20,584
No, Madam

379
00:30:20,685 --> 00:30:24,883
Are you unappy... to be alone with me?

380
00:30:25,023 --> 00:30:26,684
Oh, no, Madam... it's only that... 

381
00:30:26,758 --> 00:30:28,749
that I can't hardly believe

382
00:30:29,327 --> 00:30:31,420
all the other times aren't real

383
00:30:31,629 --> 00:30:32,960
Other times?

384
00:30:34,365 --> 00:30:38,665
I mean... at the opera when you're always
way down below on the stage

385
00:30:39,003 --> 00:30:41,130
But when your voice came after me... 

386
00:30:41,539 --> 00:30:43,336
you were wonderfully close... 

387
00:30:43,875 --> 00:30:45,433
I mean... 

388
00:30:46,744 --> 00:30:49,178
And we're alone together?

389
00:30:51,716 --> 00:30:54,116
Last time you sang <Norma>... 

390
00:30:54,552 --> 00:30:56,349
you're the only one there... 

391
00:30:56,454 --> 00:31:00,447
you and l... and the greatest voice
in the world

392
00:31:01,092 --> 00:31:02,957
The only composer I ever knew

393
00:31:03,027 --> 00:31:05,552
was fat little man with bald head

394
00:31:06,865 --> 00:31:10,392
Well, I never know further I'll be any
kind of composer or not

395
00:31:10,869 --> 00:31:15,670
All I know is when you first walked to
the Dommayer's at the night and

396
00:31:15,773 --> 00:31:17,468
I played to you

397
00:31:17,542 --> 00:31:19,305
You should know I played to you

398
00:31:19,344 --> 00:31:23,212
And just now when... you sang my waltz
before everybody

399
00:31:23,748 --> 00:31:26,182
I'm more alone with you than ever

400
00:31:27,218 --> 00:31:29,311
More alone than now?

401
00:31:42,600 --> 00:31:44,465
Sorry for being late, Carla... 

402
00:31:45,003 --> 00:31:49,133
I've an order from His Majesty... 
he's troubled sometimes

403
00:31:49,340 --> 00:31:51,274
Darling, you must be worn out

404
00:31:51,342 --> 00:31:53,902
Tony, this is the lovely young man... 

405
00:31:53,978 --> 00:31:55,309
he's a composer

406
00:31:55,380 --> 00:31:59,180
He and I have been along together
for years, haven't we?

407
00:31:59,217 --> 00:32:03,313
This is our host, Count Hohenfried... 
Mr. Strauss

408
00:32:04,289 --> 00:32:06,655
He was up in the balcony and
I was on the stage

409
00:32:06,724 --> 00:32:09,591
As a matter of fact, we're practically
sweet-hearted

410
00:32:09,627 --> 00:32:12,095
Perfect, really?

411
00:32:12,196 --> 00:32:14,528
I heard you sang a waltz too... 

412
00:32:15,366 --> 00:32:18,494
another one of your Bohemian evening
... - my darling?

413
00:32:18,569 --> 00:32:23,063
Tony... why?

414
00:32:24,742 --> 00:32:27,176
I defense... I imagine

415
00:32:27,245 --> 00:32:28,803
Thank you

416
00:32:33,217 --> 00:32:36,015
The usual fee for musician I believe
is 10 golden

417
00:32:36,054 --> 00:32:38,022
You can't insult my composer... 

418
00:32:38,089 --> 00:32:39,886
his performance is brilliant

419
00:32:39,958 --> 00:32:41,892
Very well, 50 golden

420
00:32:42,327 --> 00:32:43,885
Oh, I'm ashamed of you... 

421
00:32:43,962 --> 00:32:46,021
nothing less than 100 golden

422
00:32:46,064 --> 00:32:47,895
Alright, my dear... 100 golden

423
00:32:47,932 --> 00:32:49,490
That's more like it, honey

424
00:32:49,567 --> 00:32:50,761
Thank you, Sir

425
00:32:50,835 --> 00:32:53,030
But might need it for another necklace

426
00:32:53,338 --> 00:32:55,772
As a matter of fact, I owe you 10 times as much

427
00:32:55,807 --> 00:32:57,536
what I've learned here tonight

428
00:32:58,076 --> 00:33:00,408
The performance is great, Madam... 

429
00:33:00,945 --> 00:33:03,436
I hope you were amused

430
00:33:24,335 --> 00:33:26,701
Poldi, what are you doing here?

431
00:33:28,339 --> 00:33:31,331
Yes, well... I don't know

432
00:33:31,376 --> 00:33:33,139
What do you mean 'you don't know'?

433
00:33:35,279 --> 00:33:37,270
I'm so foolish

434
00:33:37,348 --> 00:33:41,045
I'm so sorry... it's just silly

435
00:33:42,387 --> 00:33:44,355
I got just a funny feeling

436
00:33:44,422 --> 00:33:46,652
when you went away
with the gentleman in Dommayer's

437
00:33:46,724 --> 00:33:50,820
And then suddenly I know, l... 

438
00:33:50,895 --> 00:33:53,386
I thought you were in danger

439
00:33:53,498 --> 00:33:55,159
I'm so silly

440
00:33:55,199 --> 00:34:00,034
Of course, here you're perfectly
a grown up man... perfectly alright

441
00:34:02,206 --> 00:34:05,471
I could drop some puddles on the
sidewalk

442
00:34:05,543 --> 00:34:10,003
Poldi, don't you dare drop puddles
on the sidewalk?

443
00:34:11,549 --> 00:34:13,176
Johann

444
00:34:13,384 --> 00:34:15,750
I'm a lucky fool, Poldi

445
00:34:16,287 --> 00:34:19,017
I never knew I've had this much
in your heart

446
00:34:19,357 --> 00:34:20,619
You always are

447
00:34:20,691 --> 00:34:22,886
Don't forget to turn off the light

448
00:34:22,994 --> 00:34:26,361
Oh, I was just about to arrest her, officer

449
00:34:26,531 --> 00:34:28,761
Don't you see how guilty she looks?

450
00:34:29,300 --> 00:34:32,167
I wish my wife looks guilty as that

451
00:34:34,305 --> 00:34:39,971
Oh, Johann, now I really could drop
on the sidewalk

452
00:34:41,045 --> 00:34:45,277
POLDI AND JOHANN

453
00:35:02,433 --> 00:35:03,457
Now... sit down

454
00:35:03,534 --> 00:35:04,558
Sit down, everybody

455
00:35:04,635 --> 00:35:08,071
Now comes the speech

456
00:35:09,140 --> 00:35:12,303
Fine, yeah... who can talk without wine?

457
00:35:12,543 --> 00:35:14,773
Well, who can talk without cake?

458
00:35:15,113 --> 00:35:17,638
Thank you, Madam... 
I just take a little piece

459
00:35:17,715 --> 00:35:19,410
Oh

460
00:35:25,590 --> 00:35:28,957
My friends, I should like to propose
a toss

461
00:35:29,427 --> 00:35:30,689
I'll make it short, my friend

462
00:35:30,761 --> 00:35:32,991
Kienzl is about to eat the cake

463
00:35:34,465 --> 00:35:39,994
As for Johanrs happiness, that now has
beautifully and for all times

464
00:35:40,071 --> 00:35:41,971
in Poldi's care

465
00:35:43,174 --> 00:35:45,574
I had met 100 of young men,

466
00:35:45,643 --> 00:35:48,510
but never had I met finnier young man and

467
00:35:48,579 --> 00:35:52,310
finnier musician than Johann Strauss

468
00:35:52,416 --> 00:35:54,884
Oh, that's lovely... so sweet

469
00:35:54,952 --> 00:35:56,044
Johann... speech

470
00:35:56,087 --> 00:35:57,611
Yes... come on

471
00:35:57,655 --> 00:36:00,215
Go on... say something

472
00:36:00,291 --> 00:36:04,022
That's there... say just a few words

473
00:36:07,698 --> 00:36:09,632
My darling wife... 

474
00:36:09,734 --> 00:36:11,463
My dear mother... 

475
00:36:11,602 --> 00:36:13,502
My new Mama and Papa... 

476
00:36:13,571 --> 00:36:16,165
My dear colleagues... 

477
00:36:16,340 --> 00:36:17,864
Yesterday Kienzl was a baker and

478
00:36:17,942 --> 00:36:19,170
the baker is a colleague today

479
00:36:19,210 --> 00:36:20,939
Yes, and tomorrow who knows... 

480
00:36:21,012 --> 00:36:22,502
maybe a baron or a king?

481
00:36:22,580 --> 00:36:23,478
Don't laugh... 

482
00:36:23,514 --> 00:36:26,711
Revolution is not so far away... 
my friends

483
00:36:26,751 --> 00:36:28,685
All he thinks is about being a baron

484
00:36:28,753 --> 00:36:32,245
He forgets what we're fighting for is
constitution... 

485
00:36:32,290 --> 00:36:35,225
representation... free press and free speech... 

486
00:36:35,259 --> 00:36:38,023
Sit down... go on, Johann

487
00:36:38,396 --> 00:36:40,728
Tonight I find even more than happiness

488
00:36:41,432 --> 00:36:43,992
and more than our success together

489
00:36:44,068 --> 00:36:47,231
And believe me,
you can't find it in the rich palaces

490
00:36:47,271 --> 00:36:50,240
You can't find it in hard cover the
gold bracelets or... 

491
00:36:50,308 --> 00:36:53,573
behind the falls of painted laughter

492
00:36:54,178 --> 00:36:58,512
You can't find peace in the deep quiet
breath of living there

493
00:36:58,583 --> 00:37:00,744
because that I know... 

494
00:37:00,818 --> 00:37:03,286
I know because I've found it here tonight

495
00:37:03,354 --> 00:37:06,983
in my wife... in my music

496
00:37:08,159 --> 00:37:09,319
and in my friends... 

497
00:37:09,393 --> 00:37:12,726
Bravo... wonderful

498
00:37:12,830 --> 00:37:14,058
Excellent... 

499
00:37:14,131 --> 00:37:16,156
I mean perfect... I mean bravo... 

500
00:37:16,234 --> 00:37:17,132
Bravo

501
00:37:17,235 --> 00:37:18,202
Yes, thank you

502
00:37:18,269 --> 00:37:21,238
Mr. Hofbauer... the music publisher

503
00:37:21,305 --> 00:37:22,067
Mr. Hofbauer?

504
00:37:22,139 --> 00:37:22,867
Yeah

505
00:37:22,940 --> 00:37:23,599
Good evening, Sir

506
00:37:23,641 --> 00:37:25,233
They told me I could find you here

507
00:37:25,309 --> 00:37:26,503
They told me you just got married

508
00:37:26,577 --> 00:37:27,271
Yes, Sir

509
00:37:27,345 --> 00:37:28,505
Well, don't worry

510
00:37:28,579 --> 00:37:31,343
We're once in a while... we're both
in the same goal together

511
00:37:31,415 --> 00:37:34,043
I mean we're in the same boat together... 
same boat together

512
00:37:34,118 --> 00:37:34,846
This is my wife

513
00:37:34,952 --> 00:37:36,180
Oh, how do you do... ?

514
00:37:36,220 --> 00:37:38,552
You know your waltz has created
quite a big splash

515
00:37:38,623 --> 00:37:40,250
Well, it's not so big splash... 

516
00:37:40,358 --> 00:37:41,586
it's just a mild splash

517
00:37:41,659 --> 00:37:42,751
I had a few offers

518
00:37:42,860 --> 00:37:44,851
By the way, I have a contract here
for you to sign... 

519
00:37:44,929 --> 00:37:46,157
sort of a wedding present

520
00:37:46,230 --> 00:37:47,458
Johann... a contract?

521
00:37:47,565 --> 00:37:48,896
Do you have quill pen?

522
00:37:48,966 --> 00:37:49,523
Yeah, I'll get it

523
00:37:49,600 --> 00:37:51,568
That's 1,000 golden for a year
for your waltz

524
00:37:51,636 --> 00:37:53,126
1,000 golden a year?

525
00:37:53,204 --> 00:37:56,105
Oh, Johann... who said you can't earn
money writing a waltz?

526
00:37:56,173 --> 00:37:58,266
I always believe in being generous to
young composers

527
00:37:58,309 --> 00:37:59,776
Here, just sign here... sign here

528
00:37:59,810 --> 00:38:01,209
I'm sorry, Mr. Hofbauer... 

529
00:38:01,279 --> 00:38:02,746
but this is not enough

530
00:38:03,080 --> 00:38:04,069
Not enough?

531
00:38:04,148 --> 00:38:05,342
Are you joking?

532
00:38:05,383 --> 00:38:06,407
Here go on... sign

533
00:38:06,517 --> 00:38:07,609
No... 

534
00:38:07,652 --> 00:38:09,244
I mean it... the golden is down

535
00:38:09,320 --> 00:38:10,480
We're headed for an inflation... 

536
00:38:10,554 --> 00:38:13,182
the discount rate might go to 20%

537
00:38:13,257 --> 00:38:14,918
Oh, no, not 1,000 golden a year... 

